HEPATITIS A - CZECH REPUBLIC
****************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Tue 23 Sep 2008
Source: Radio Praga (Trans. from Span. by Mod.MPP) [edited]
<http://www.radio.cz/es/articulo/108545>


Czech Republic struggles to combat an outbreak of hepatitis A
-------------------------------------------------------------
An outbreak of hepatitis A has affected the Czech
Republic since July [2008]. Although the
epicenter is still Prague, the disease has
already spread to Central Bohemia, and some cases
were also reported from North Moravia.

Approximately 130 people developed symptoms of
hepatitis A in the Czech Republic in 2007. This
year [2008] approximately 440 cases have been
identified and their number is increasing. The
worst situation is seen in Prague, where some 260
infected individuals have been reported "Dozens
of people are still waiting for the results of
blood tests, so the number of infected could rise
significantly within a week," said Michael Vit,
the Director General of Health Services of the Czech Republic.

The mayor of Prague has taken steps to halt the
spread of the disease. In early September [2008],
a mass vaccination of drug addicts and homeless
people was conducted -- that is, the groups at
highest risk. Recently there have been
approximately 40 000 Euros [USD 58 578.00]
earmarked for the disinfection of primary schools
and public transportation, said the health
councilor, Milan Pesek. "We have gone ahead with
the disinfection of public transport means and
urban primary schools last weekend and will
continue with the measure until the situation improves in Prague," noted Pesek.

Central Bohemia detected about 60 individuals
infected with hepatitis A [virus], the largest
number of which live in the cities of Pardubice
and Hradec Kralove. Also the city of Frydek
Mystek in North Moravia, has reported their 1st
cases. According to Michael Vit, the number of
people infected will continue to grow for a
month, at a minimum, and will culminate in late
October or early November [2008] [Interestingly,
here there was the use of the future tense rather
than the conditional tense, presenting a posture
of certainty that the cases will continue and
also the certainty that the epidemic will end by
the estimated timeframe -- late October or early November 2008 - Mod.MPP].

Hepatitis A is transmitted through [contact with
infected] urine, blood and sexual contact.
Although it [hepatitis A] is not as dangerous as
hepatitis B and C, it has a complicated treatment
and spreads easily. [In the overwhelming majority
of cases, there is no real specific treatment
other than avoidance of contact with hepatotoxic
agents such as acetaminophen, and alcohol to name
a few. - Mod.MPP] To prevent transmission,
experts recommend washing hands frequently and
avoid sharing hygiene and personal use products.

[Byline: Katerina Oratorova]

--
