[According to the World Health Organisation
hepatitis A, one of the oldest diseases known to
humankind, is a self-limited disease which
results in fulminant hepatitis and death in only
a small proportion of patients. However, it is a
significant cause of morbidity and socio-economic
losses in many parts of the world. Transmission
of hepatitis A virus is typically by the
faecal-oral route. Infections occur early in life
in areas where sanitation is poor and living
conditions are crowded. With improved sanitation
and hygiene, infections are delayed and
consequently the number of persons susceptible to
the disease increases. Under these conditions
explosive epidemics can arise from faecal
contamination of a single source. As almost all
hepatitis A virus infections are spread by the
faecal-oral route, good personal hygiene, high
quality standards for public water supplies and
proper disposal of sanitary waste have resulted
in a low prevalence of hepatitis A virus
infections in many well developed societies.

In some regions of industrialized countries where
sanitary conditions are variable (Southern and
Eastern Europe), children escape infection in
early childhood. Paradoxically, these improved
economic and sanitary conditions may lead to a
higher disease incidence, as infections occur in
older age groups, and reported rates of
clinically evident hepatitis A are higher.The
rise in hepatitis A cases in the Czech Republic
may be due as much to infrastructural problems as
to the presence of foreign immigrants and
homeless people, particularly since targeting
these groups for vaccination does not seem to be
effective in containing the spread of infection.

The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of the
Czech Republic is available at:
<http://healthmap.org/promed?v=49.7,15.3,5>. - Mod.CP]
